      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Pawla of Edessa</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Pawla-of-Edessa</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/424</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">415</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="322"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/84</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Metropolitan of <placeName>Edessa</placeName> and translator.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(early 7th <abbr>cent.</abbr>) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Metropolitan of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Edessa">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName>
                        </ref> and
                        translator. His careful revision of an earlier translation of <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Gregory-of-Nazianzus">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/511">Gregory of Nazianzus</persName>
                        </ref>’s Discourses survives complete; this was
                        done while he was in Cyprus in 623/4, during the Persian invasion and
                        occupation of Mesopotamia. Another large undertaking while he was in Cyprus
                        was the translation of a collection of hymns (<hi rend="italic">maʿnyoto</hi>) by <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Severus-of-Antioch">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/51">Severus</persName>
                        </ref> ‘according to the
                        tradition of <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Qenneshre-Monastery-of">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/230">Qenneshre</placeName>
                        </ref>’, that was later to be revised
                        by <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Yaqub-of-Edessa">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/113">Yaʿqub of Edessa</persName>
                        </ref> (<abbr>ed.</abbr> E. W. Brooks, in <abbr>PO</abbr> 6.1, 7.5; 1910–11). He
                        is probably also the ‘Abbas Pawla’ who translated the pericope John
                        7:50–8:12, absent from the <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Peshitta">Peshitta</ref> and <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Harqlean-Version">Ḥarqlean</ref>. He is commemorated in one liturgical
                        calendar (<abbr>PO</abbr> 10, 124) on 23 Aug. (‘Pawla, <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Edessa, who translated the
                        books’).</p>
                </div>
